#    ░▀░▀░▀▀▀░▀▀▀░░▀░░▀░▀▀▀░░▀░░▀░▀░░▀░░▀▀▀

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# File Purpose
#   Analyzes the shell history file to provide a visual breakdown of the user's
#   most frequently used commands.
#
# Problems Solved
#   - Aggregates raw history data into meaningful usage patterns.
#   - Normalizes commands (e.g., stripping 'sudo' or 'time' prefixes and paths).
#   - Filters out high-frequency "noise" commands (ls, cd, etc.) to highlight
#     actual tool usage.
#   - Visualizes frequency through a color-coded TUI bar chart.
#
# Features / Responsibilities
#   - Command Normalization: Extracts the core binary name from paths or wrappers.
#   - Advanced AWK Pipeline: Handles data aggregation and bar width calculation.
#   - Heatmap Bars: Colors bars based on the percentage of total command volume.
#   - Dashboard UI: Displays total analyzed vs. unique command count.
#
# Usage Notes
#   - Syntax: hist_stats
#   - Relies on the 'fc' (fix command) builtin to read history.
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------


# ── history analysis engine ──────────────────────────────────────────────────




# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1. Environment Sandbox

# emulate -L zsh: Restricts configuration changes to this local scope.
# pipefail: Ensures that if any command in the pipe fails, the whole chain fails.
emulate -L zsh
setopt localoptions no_xtrace pipefail


# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 2. Filtering Configuration

# Regex pattern to ignore utility commands that don't represent "work"
local ignore_pattern="^(ls|cd|clear|exit|z|zsh|pwd|history|exec|source|sudo)$"

print "${COLOR[BLUE]}::${COLOR[RESET]} Analyzing command history..."

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 3. Processing Pipeline

# --- Complex Logic: Data Aggregation ---
# 1. fc -l -n 1: Lists all history commands without line numbers.
# 2. AWK Logic:
#    - Skips prefixes like 'sudo' to find the actual command being run.
#    - Strips directory paths (e.g., /usr/bin/git -> git).
#    - Increments a hash map 'count[cmd]' for every valid entry.
local output
output=$(fc -l -n 1 | LC_ALL=C awk -v ignore="$ignore_pattern" '
{
    cmd = $1
    # Extract true command if wrapped in common utility wrappers
    if (cmd == "sudo" || cmd == "time") cmd = $2

    # Handle absolute or relative paths: find basename
    n = split(cmd, parts, "/")
    if (n > 1) cmd = parts[n]

    # Filter out noise, empty lines, or variable assignments
    if (cmd == "" || cmd ~ /^(\.|\/)/ || cmd ~ /=/ || cmd ~ ignore) next

    count[cmd]++
    total++
}
END {
    print "TOTAL_CMDS " total
    for (c in count) print count[c] " " c
}' | sort -nr)

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 4. Result Parsing

# Extract calculated metrics from the AWK output stream
local total_cmds=$(print "$output" | grep "TOTAL_CMDS" | cut -d' ' -f2)
local data=$(print "$output" | grep -v "TOTAL_CMDS")
local top_15=$(print "$data" | head -n 15)
local unique_count=$(print "$data" | wc -l | tr -d ' ')

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 5. Dashboard Rendering

print "${COLOR[BLUE]}╭──────────────────────────────────────────────────╮${COLOR[RESET]}"
print "${COLOR[BLUE]}│             📊  COMMAND HISTORY STATS            │${COLOR[RESET]}"
print "${COLOR[BLUE]}├──────────────────────────────────────────────────┤${COLOR[RESET]}"

# 1. Define the exact text lengths and the middle gap (6 spaces)
local text_analyzed="Analyzed: $total_cmds"
local text_unique="Unique: $unique_count"
local middle_gap="      "

# 2. Calculate remaining space to distribute
local visible_len=$(( ${#text_analyzed} + ${#middle_gap} + ${#text_unique} ))
local remaining=$(( 50 - visible_len ))

# 3. Split the remaining space evenly for perfect centering
local left_pad=$(( remaining / 2 ))
local right_pad=$(( remaining - left_pad )) # Handles odd numbers gracefully

# 4. Generate the exact whitespace strings
local space_left="" space_right=""
(( left_pad > 0 )) && printf -v space_left "%*s" $left_pad ""
(( right_pad > 0 )) && printf -v space_right "%*s" $right_pad ""

# 5. Print the perfectly centered row
print "${COLOR[BLUE]}│${COLOR[RESET]}${space_left}Analyzed: ${COLOR[WHITE]}${total_cmds}${COLOR[RESET]}${middle_gap}Unique: ${COLOR[WHITE]}${unique_count}${COLOR[RESET]}${space_right}${COLOR[BLUE]}│${COLOR[RESET]}"

print "${COLOR[BLUE]}╰──────────────────────────────────────────────────╯${COLOR[RESET]}"

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 6. Bar Chart Rendering

# --- Complex Logic: Heatmap Generation ---
# We map the percentage of usage to a color scale and bar width.
# 1. pct > 20% -> Red (Major Reliance)
# 2. pct > 10% -> Orange
# 3. pct > 5%  -> Yellow
# 4. else      -> Green
print "$top_15" | awk -v total="$total_cmds" '
function get_color(pct) {
    if (pct > 20) return "\033[38;5;196m"
    if (pct > 10) return "\033[38;5;214m"
    if (pct > 5)  return "\033[38;5;226m"
    return "\033[38;5;46m"
}
{
    count = $1
    cmd = $2
    percent = (total > 0) ? (count / total) * 100 : 0

    # Scale the bar width (capped at 20 characters)
    bar_width = int(percent / 1.5)
    if (bar_width == 0 && percent > 0) bar_width = 1
    if (bar_width > 20) bar_width = 20

    # Build Unicode bar string
    bar = ""
    for (i=0; i<bar_width; i++) bar = bar "▇"

    color = get_color(percent)
    reset = "\033[0m"
    grey  = "\033[38;5;240m"
    white = "\033[1;37m"

    # Final Dashboard Print (Using standard AWK printf)
    printf "  %s%4d%s  %s%5.1f%%%s  %s%-12s%s  %s%s%s\n",
        white, count, reset,
        grey, percent, reset,
        white, cmd, reset,
        color, bar, reset
}'
print
